inn1.comm: tighter onto the pads this time, and tickled away to fine leg to get off the mark
this time it's outside Vaughan's off stump, gently swinging towards the slips, and left well alone
wider, and called as much. McGrath mutters to himself as he huffs back to his mark. Oh the indignity
straying onto the right-hander's pads, and clipped into space at midwicket. Both openers are up and running
a good ball to finish, just short of a length, in that corridor, and Strauss lets it go with the bat tucked inside the line
oops, a rare fumble from Adam Gilchrist lets the batsmen cross for a single. Not the tidiest ball ever delivered, in fairness
opens the face, and runs this one down to third man
the first boundary of the day, and appropriately - in the context of England's summer so far - it's a streaky one! Inside-edge of a forward defensive, and it flies down to fine leg
good length again, turned off the pads but straight to midwicket
well played, uses the pace of the ball to run it past backward point. There we go, I remembered that one
Nearly back up to date - bet you can't wait!
tight wicket-to-wicket delivery, and turned into the slips
beautiful shot! That's vintage Vaughan, short of a length and pulled imperiously in front of square. The best shot he's played in Australia for four years, I'll wager
a wide swinging half-volley from McGrath, and Vaughan is onto it like a flash, square-driving all the way to the fence. Kum-bya-yar Michael Vaughan!

right, we are officially back up to speed. What a total shambles. Apologies for all that, but it's the end of the first powerplay, and time to take stock. A decent start for England by their recent standards, but Michael Vaughan's dismissal for 26 has tilted the balance to Australia
time to regroup for England, and for Cricinfo, and Bell starts with a watchful defensive stroke
wicket-to-wicket delivery, and another perpendicular face of the bat
wider this time, and slapped into the covers to bring the big dog, KP, onto strike
a thickish outside-edge to get off the mark, beats the field but pulls up inside the rope
up and onto his toes, and driven square to a diving Michael Clarke at point, who roars with anguish that he failed to field it cleanly. Perfectionists, these Aussies.
outside off stump, and left well alone
a controlled slash from Pietersen goes straight through the gap at fourth slip, and arrives at third man on the second bounce
driven firmly, but can't beat the field
good length delivery and a hurried defensive prod
lovely delivery! Saw Pietersen looking to advance, and hit the deck extra hard, with the ball zipping off a good length and just missing the edge of the bat
defensive once again, and a slight inside-edge onto the pads. Lovely over
nice start from Clark - just back of a length, wobbly seam, watchful defence
more of the same. He's found that awkward length already
slightly wider this time, but a checked drive can't beat the field
fuller and straighter onto the pads, and clipped to the man at short midwicket
nothing more than the basics here for Clark, but they are mighty effective. Back of a length once again, and a dot ball once again
slightly shorter, jabbing up towards Bell's ribs, and that's fended away for a scampered single. The end of a lovely tight over
fast arm, but a bit wide of off stump first up. Left well alone
awkward lifter, again on off stump. Bell negotiates with a flick of the wrists into the gully again
more comfortable line and length for the batsman, and that's pushed coolly into the covers
swinging into the pads, Bell misses out on a flick through midwicket
a more forceful, front-foot drive, but again, there's no beating the field. A maiden to start Johnson's spell
on the pads and flicked away, but a brilliant sprawling stop from Ponting at midwicket. The Aussies are electric in the field
he's on the walk again, three casual steps down the track, followed by a cool pushed defence.
opens the face and plays into the gully
on the pads again, and flicked in the air through the vacant square leg
leg side and called. A rare aberration
down the pitch again, and tucked away to midwicket
not an easy time out there for Bell at the moment. He's a bit fidgetty at the crease and can't get this one away through the gully
leg-side, and played off the back foot to midwicket
a wild flog of a shot through the covers, but again KP can't beat the field. It's a war of attrition out there
KP tries to find room in the gully this time, but can't
the frustration is palpable. Still no way through. Johnson hasn't conceded a run in ten deliveries
he has now! And it's a streaky slash through the vacant slip cordon, and all the way to the boundary. Well, they all count
another rash drive, but this time the ball fizzes through to the keeper. Another fine over
at last, some welcome runs for Bell, steered past point to the boundary
on the back foot, turned to short midwicket
lovely delivery. Tight on the stumps, Pietersen can only offer a straight bat, and he's lucky not to get the edge as the ball whistles through
that's the shot! He's been looking for that one ever since he came to the crease, but this time Pietersen walks straight into an effortless straight drive. He's starting to find his range now ...
on the back foot again, and tucked to midwicket
outside off stump, and left well alone
shuffled across his stumps and picked up at midwicket
good length delivery, driven straight down the ground. Cut off by mid-off, but he can't stop the single

Gottim! And you have to say that was coming! Johnson's been turning the screw superbly since he came on, and this time Bell couldn't hold himself back - down the track, and a loose drive straight to mid-off, comfortably lodged in Mike Hussey's midriff
off the mark instantly with a nudge through square leg, but England have a bit of regrouping to do here
not timed, but effective as the ball pulls up inside the fine leg rope. How much now rests on this man ...
lodged on the back foot, and unable to find any gaps at midwicket
not the best of throws, and Collingwood quite possibly should have been on his way there! Back for two, and Hayden's throw from mid-on has the batsman sprawling at the non-striker's end
another flick, another couple of runs, but safer this time as the throw comes in from deep midwicket
onto the back foot and defended watchfully
onto the front foot, by way of a change, but it's the same result&
outside off stump, Collingwood takes a swish but the ball keeps a touch low and scuttles through to the keeper
brilliantly nagging line-and-length bowling going on here. Collingwood connects this time, but can't apply any pace to the ball
still in that off-stump corridor, and defended with a late shuffle
banged in back of a length, angled across towards the slips. And another dot ball
on the legs, but still no way to whip it away. England are under the cosh here
trouble here! Ponting dives, fields, rolls and flings, but just misses the stumps from midwicket. Collingwood would have been out for all money. Brilliant stuff
more watchful in defence, as Collingwood continues to struggle to double his runs tally&
nudged into the leg side with minimal foot movement, and there it is. He's doubled his tally
Shot! A perfect straight drive - an easy stride followed by a full flowing bat. Shaves the stumps at the non-striker's end, and all the way to the fence
more brilliant fielding, this time from Andrew Symonds in the covers
tucked off the hips to keep the strike, but it's a no-ball, so one more to come
firm wallop through the off side, but nicely intercepted at point by Michael Clarke
more positive intent from Pietersen as he comes down the track, and edges a drive down to third man
pushed to cover, but with no power
lovely ball, gently but deceptively swinging, and beats Collingwood's loose drive
up in the air ... but safe! That was a loose pull from Collingwood, but it spiralled just out of the reach of Symonds, running back from mid-on
good length again, and pushed into the leg side
solid back-foot defence. But solidity isn't the be-all and end-all
pushed into the covers once again. God, England are rubbish at one-dayers
on the back foot, and turned to square leg
a big hooning drive, but again no timing. Picked up in the covers, as the pressure ticks up again
back and defends. At least there are still wickets intact
driven into the gap at long-on, but no freebies on offer
glanced to backward square leg
nope, no way through there
nor there. Lovely tight bowling from Johnson. That left-arm angle is toying with Collingwood's mind
opens the face and attempts to pick up a single, but Pietersen rightly sends him back
oooh ... lucky lucky! Fended into space behind point, but Collingwood should have been run out as he dived for his second run. The pressure is really telling out there for England
a thickish drive brings up England's 100
tidy loop and decent line,
flighted delivery and pushed into the covers
more width this time, but the same result. Pressure, pressure
good loop and flight, and glanced down to fine leg
full onto the stumps and pushed into the covers
slower delivery, and a mistimed flick is the result from Collingwood
back of a length and slapped out to the cover sweeper
a rare couple for the struggling Collingwood, who slaps the ball off the front foot to cover
lovely ball, angled away from the right-hander, and just eludes the edge as well
good flight and loop, Clarke is not afraid to tease the England batsmen at the moment
down on one knee and paddled away for a single
another paddle, and another single.
cut, or late cut, but straight to point. Still can't find the gap
full and straight, clipped down to mid-on
fuller still and Collingwood times this back to the bowler
on leg stump this time but Collingwood, despite whipping it forcefully off the back foot, can't find the gap at midwicket
and it's a touch shorter this time, Collingwood goes for a delicate late glance but misses
and eventually he gets a run, clunking it off the back foot - but the length was again excellent from Bracken and Collingwood can't time it
swept without power to a short fine leg
ooh, lovely shot punching it straight down the ground but just for a single
delicately reverse swept down to third man
ooh and he goes for it again but misses, and is hit on the pad
punched down the ground
excellently bowled; he saw the batsman coming down the track and banged it down short, and on his pads, preventing him from driving

whipped off his legs to White at deep midwicket, it's in the air and going straight down his throat - but no! The sun beats him! He makes a total hash of it, ducking his head and the ball bobbles over for four
worked off his pads for a single
pushed down the ground
good, tight bowling; on middle stump and it's defended off the back foot
driven on the front foot but straight to cover
a little wider of the off stump but it's just short of a length and Collingwood can't time it. Again.
Pietersen has absolutely hammered this straight back to Clarke...bump ball, but that would've stung
"noice" shouts Gilchrist to one on leg stump which Pietersen pings to mid on
on leg stump and he works it to leg
just a touch shorter of a length and it's punched off the back foot through midwicket
and he meets the length of this, sweeping it fine - timing it nicely, too
punched to midwicket and Pietersen raws a Neanderthalesque "no"
just outside off, the googly which Collingwood reads - I think - and he cuts it without timing
full, on middle stump and it's well timed down the ground
Pietersen comes down the track but White sees him and it hits his pad
just outside off, the big non-turner from White again and Pietersen prods it to cover
Pietersen comes massively forward, driving to mid on
worked through midwicket and they scamper two
neatly swept to fine leg, who is quite deep, for two
timed, not whacked, to cover
half a shuffle down the pitch from Pietersen but Clarke adjusts his length and the batsman can only clunk it to mid on
pushed to mid on
shot; that's more like it from England. Collingwood hits this over extra cover - Clarke, Gilchrist and just about everyone else cries "catch" but it's very well placed
defended on the front foot
Pietersen comes down the track to make this into a full bunger, but it hits too high on the bat and it's clunked to mid on
defended on the front foot
ooh, a nice bit of indrift but Pietersen clunks it to mid on
bash! That's the way to do it, hitting it over extra cover - high and handsome for six. That was a beaut.
pushed down the ground
Collingwood defends this on the front foot. Gilchrist "loves" it apparently.
down the pitch confidently and punched to long on
and Collingwood comes down the pitch this time but can only push it back to the bowler
expansively driven but straight to cover
a very nice late cut, delicately played
the wrong line from Clarke, drifting down leg and it's easily turned round the corner for a single
down the pitch and pushed, without great power or timing, for a single
chipped over short midwicket, "catch" is the cry from Gilchrist but it's neatly placed
swept on the full down to fine leg, very well played
down the pitch and Pietersen pings this straight into Collingwood's knee. Ouch. Just short of the knee in fact
oh yes, that's massive. Ping pang, and Pietersen smashes this over long on
here we go! Straighter this time, Pietersen crashes it over the bowler's head, flatter. But the same result
timed down - and along - the ground
punched down the ground on the front foot
that's the right length, nice and full and straight
on leg stump and it's well timed, albeit without much power, to long on
ooh and Pietersen shuffles across, and down, the pitch and sweeps it to fine leg
an ugly reverse sweep from Collingwood. Not timed
down the pitch but Collingwood again can't time it
full, on off stump and Collingwood check-drives this past McGrath, down the ground and Mitchell Johnson sprints from long-on to save four. Excellent fielding
the slower ball from McGrath, Collingwood picks it but can't execute this lofted shot as well as he might and it's hit straight to Johnson at long on
ooh and a welcoming bouncer from McGrath, Flintoff ducks out of the way
well bowled! Full, inswinging yorker which Flintoff digs out
oh dear, a very ugly, concrete-footed swish outside his off stump from Flintoff
angled off the back foot to Clarke at backward point. They go for a single, oh no they don't - Clarke sends in a throw and Pietersen dives back in his crease at the non-striker's end
full and straight and hit down the ground once more, but without sufficient power
drifting down the leg side and Flintoff turns his wrists, placing this through midwicket for a single
he stands tall here, elegantly driving it down the ground
slog swept with immense power over deep midwicket. Calmly, solidly smashed
defended on the front foot
ooh, excellent bouncer which is quickly evaded by the batsman
shot! What an extraordinary shot just for a single, down the pitch and slapping it through midwicket
swinging into Flintoff's pads who gives himself a touch of room outside leg, opening the face and guiding it to cover
smashed with a flourish but he can't find the gap at extra cover
deliciously driven down the ground with the straightest of bats. Again, a marvellous shot just for a single though

ouch. Pietersen skips down the pitch to a bouncer and is struck in the chest. Gilchrist pops over for a sledge, as does McGrath and Symonds makes it a trio of insults. No surprise there, given how Pietersen has skipped down the wicket to McGrath all summer (or winter, depending where you live). It just bounced a touch too much, cannoning into his ribs and he slumps to the ground.
clunked into the covers
Flintoff waits for this on the back foot and bashes it off the back foot through the covers
shorter, Pietersen tries to pull but can't time it
glanced off the back foot
angled behind square, Clarke is so quick to run round, picks up one-handed and sends in a decent throw
pushed into the covers
swinging away down the leg side. Not quite the start we've come to expect
good length delivery, heaved to long-on, and McGrath fumbles to make a second a formality
a low full-bunger, and clobbered straight down the ground with immense power and timing! Shot, Freddie!
wild swish and a top-edge, but it lands safe and sound. Flintoff fights on
down on one knee and an extravagant drive, followed by a grimace. Those ribs are still smarting
attempted yorker, punched into space on the leg-side. Useful stand building here
cracked rib or no cracked rib. That's another single
short, and pulled to deep midwicket
short, and walloped! Flat and fast, over cow corner for four! Flintoff is on a mission to make amends for the Test series
gives himself room, and squeezes another single past point. He's looking much more relaxed at the crease today ...
good rotation of the strike
makes room again, but can't find the gap
a big swish, once again, and a deflection off the pads. All the same, a decent over for England, who have a shot at 260 if these two keep goings
yorker length, and blocked back down the pitch
big swish again, and another run is the result as the ball bobbles into the covers
banged in, and biffed over backward square leg! Pulled off the front foot, which is quite some feat. Even if he does jerk his head back at the last minute

another vast swipe ... and it's swirling, swirling, swirling down to Andrew Symonds, just inside the long-on boundary! A massive breakthrough for Australia, and Pietersen is gone, just when he was looking at his most dangerous
full and straight, dug out by Nixon
on off stump this time but it's too full for Nixon who can only clunk it back to the bowler
ooh and Flintoff tries to smash this through extra cover but it's too full, and too quick and he misses out
nearly! Well bowled, Johnson; he held that one back, Flintoff drove it on the up but it fell agonisingly short of McGrath at backward point
clunked, heavy-footed and heavy-batted, into the covers. Ungainly shot, that, and without his customary massive power
Nixon turns the face of the bat, pushing it to mid on

gone! Full, straight and that would've plucked out his leg stump. Excellent length from Johnson and with a touch of away swing to the left hander who, trying to work it to leg, was beaten by pace...and up goes the finger
good ball, quick and straight and Dalrymple digs it out with a lot of bottom hand
very full but not yorker-length-full, Flintoff digs it out and times it past Clark for a quick, and well-run, single
neatly played by Dalrymple, just angling the face of the bat down to third man
calmly played by Flintoff, stepping outside his off stump and punching it to the bowler's right. No great intent or power in that stroke, just content to pick up the single
that's nicely bowled from Clark, cramping Dalrymple for room who can't time it sufficiently
and he pushes this out into the covers
full and straight again - Clark is the perfect man for Australia in these dying overs - but Dalrymple places this well, just to mid-off's left
right on the money as usual, just outside off stump and this one cuts back into the batsman who defends off the back foot
boshed to mid off but it's Michael Clarke positioned there...not a man you take a single to

down the leg side, Dalymple tries to hook this and misses. Gilchrist politely asks the umpire who, after a couple of seconds, raises his finger! What a shocker that is. Replays indicate the ball hit his helmet, and Dalrymple trudges off fairly fuming
oh nicely played from Lewis, just angling this down to third man
excellent bowling, an inswinging yorker which Flintoff digs out back to the bowler
again it's too full for Flintoff to get hold of it and he can only clunk it into the covers
the full bunger on leg stump which hurries Flintoff somewhat, who turns it through midwicket looking for two...but only a single is on offer
full, into Lewis's pads who is beaten by the inswing. Startled, he realises the ball has bobbled out into the off side and Flintoff hurries him through for a single
bish bash bosh! Just short of a length, in Flintoff's area and he simply lifts this just wide of long-on for a resounding four
pushed through midwicket for a single. Oh, they're going for two and they get it comfortably
swinging into Flintoff's pads, a full toss which he bashes down the ground
again a full toss; again an England batsman can't do enough with it, just pushing it down the ground
very full, swinging into Lewis who tries to smear it through cover but gets a thin edge, falling short of Gilchrist, and they manage to steal a single
forced past extra cover for a single
well bowled! Excellent cricket from McGrath, full, straight, swinging into Lewis who, to his credit, dug this out well
again it's a touch too full from McGrath and Flintoff is cramped for room, just meekly prodding it down to long-on for another single
reasonably aggressive shot from Lewis, giving himself room and hitting over the top
smeared through cover
clunked into the covers

what a catch! A full toss which Lewis sliced off a thick outside edge just to Ponting's right at backward point, and he dived brilliantly taking the ball horizontally, one-handed. Quite superb fielding
Flintoff pumps this down the ground to long-on, oh and they're going for two - Symonds throws to the wrong end, and Monty is like grease lightning between the wickets
shot! Freddie steps outside his off stump and swivels this over deep midwicket. Fabulous
again steps outside his off stump, meets this on the full and it's timed through midwicket - and they steal a single. Oh no, they're going for two
pushed through the covers

inn2.comm: wide of the off stump, very wide in fact. Two bounces to the keeper
oops, that's awful. Leg-side and swinging and all the way to the boundary
almost another one, taken in front of first slip by a tumbling Nixon
short of a length, pushed into the covers.
more of the same, better line
wide and slashed, and a big ooh from the keeper
that's poor, poor bowling. Wide and loose, and deflected past first slip by the keeper
and a dot to finish a frenetic first over!
that's the way to do it, good line, good length, respectfully played
too straight, and glanced fine for the first runs off the bat
that's the spot. Tight on middle and off
steady and on the spot from Lewis
bit too straight again, and worked off the pads
a bit wild from Lewis again, and England's extras tally in 2007 is already out of control
oh deary me. Leg-side, swinging, rubbish. England's competitive 242 is already an insubstantial 229
back on the spot at last. Indifferent stuff from England!
that is a beautiful shot! Once again, a bit too wide from Flintoff, and that was cracked on the up, off the back foot, with a ramrod straight bat, clean through the covers
tighter line, but it's all relative. England are all over the place at the moment
cracked off the back foot, too wide, and smashed to gully
and he gives himself a touch of room, crashing this through extra cover for three. Really well timed, and Mahmood gives chase
a tighter line this time, just outside off stump and Hayden lunges forward, defending on the front foot - albeit with a closed face of the bat
trundly pace and a fraction too much width. Nudged down to third man for a single
back of a length and pushed to cover
another fumble from cymbals Nixon, on his ODI debut. Late swing deceived him there
shapes to play a pull, and deflects off his ample midriff for a single
a modicum of control now being applied by England. Not before time
outside off stump again, left well alone and through to the keeper. Tidier over, just two runs coming from it
pushed into the gap and they cross for a single
good full length, and was that a hint of swing? Conceivably ...
no swing on that occasion, only a full swing of the bat as an Anderson long-hop is deposited over midwicket.
a bit of a scamper there for Gilchrist as Flintoff shies from mid-off and hits as well. But the batsman is safely home.
short and slightly leg-side, but Hayden misses out with a swivel-pull. One more to the tally though, as the ball bobbles into no-man's land
fuller length, and played slightly uneasily by Gilchrist, who looks back in alarm as he loses sight of the ball. No dangers though, and he's called through. Good running between these two, as ever
width, and flogged over the covers. Didn't quite time it, but no matter - it's four
now that's timing! A fraction too full, and a free swing of the blade sends the ball spiralling over Flintoff's head at long-on!
tighter, but the intent is still there from a pumped-up Gilly
width again, and heaved into the off side. Just bounces short of Panesar at deep point
at last, some respite for England, as the less frenetic Hayden comes onto strike
good finish, but another loose over for England. Australia already in absolute command of this run-chase
left alone outside off. Good line, that
full and swinging away, drilled square but fielded at point
better stuff from Anderson. Consistent line and length, and a bit of disconcerting movement too.
zippy line and length, and that's respectfully defended with Gilchrist up on his toes. Now, can he finish his good work this over?
good ball, but an even better stroke from Gilchrist, and a comedy attempt at a relay throw as Panesar fumbles a lob back from the deep midwicket rope
tidy over, and some good movement through the air. There is a bit of assistance going on out there
launched into the leg-side, and Mahmood fields well, stooping with one hand to cut off a certain boundary
pushed to cover off the front foot
short, and clobbered through midwicket with a flat bat! Hayden advanced, Lewis saw him coming, but his attempt to drag the ball down merely turned into the juiciest of long-hops
oops, another extra to the tally. Otherwise a tidy length as Hayden leaves well alone
Action replay, minus the overstep, of course
turned to square leg
back of a length, scampered single
flicked off the back foot, finds the gap at fine leg
and yet more clobberage! Full length, even fuller swing of the blade, rockets to the long-off fence
nicely angled into the left-hander, and pushed back down the pitch
the round-the-wicket line is working to Gilchrist. Though we've heard that refrain before ...
bit too much width, and a quick-footed cut to third man
straighter and on a good length. Met with a solid defence
that's better already. Well, at least it was a dot ball
tighter line, and solidly played. Well fielded in Flintoff's followthrough
pushed onto the back foot, and flicked to midwicket for one
shoulders arms outside off stump. Better from Flintoff
fuller length, on off stump. Drilled into the deep where the cover sweeper tidies up
ooh, a thick edge, but safe and away down to third man
tighter, and respectfully played
wham! Too much width, and that's launched over the covers with a full-blooded swing!
shuffles across and played out to deep midwicket
short and hammered up and over midwicket, and crosses the rope on the second bounce. Loose stuff again from England
yet more runs! Short and pulled in front of square - it looked like it came off the toe, but pretty effective nonetheless. Pure power
blimey! That's huge! A vast swing of the blade, and that's still going up as it crosses the rope at long-on. Nice catch in the crowd, by a bloke on his mobile phone!
a dot ball. Some respite for England
short of a length, and outside off stump, and cut away for two more. England are leaking runs all over the place at the moment. Did I say leaking? It's a torrent
good flight and a decent length to start from Monty
and there's his fifty! Well batted Gilly. Brought up with a nudge into the covers. It's his 47th in ODI cricket, which ain't a bad return&
width, and slapped behind point
outside off stump, and pushed away without much fuss
pushed out to cover
turned off his legs but straight to midwicket
got him! Gilchrist goes for the late cut but gets a thick outside edge to Nixon, behind the stumps, who takes an excellent catch
oh, what a shot; down the pitch and Hayden hammers it, with supreme power, straight back past the bowler
on off stump, turning back into the batsman who turns his wrists
defended on the front foot
and it's outside his off stump, Gilchrist goes back and defends off the back foot
got him! Outside Gilchrist's off stump, it turns a fraction away from his attempted cut stroke...a thick outside edge to Nixon who takes a fine catch. Big wicket
just short of a length, turning quite markedly back into the right hander who pushes it to leg
pushed through midwicket
clonked into the covers
defended on the front foot
too short and it's easily paddled by Ponting around the corner
nice length from Monty, just outside his off stump and Ponting pushes this out into the covers
pushed through midwicket
defended on the back foot
and he comes down the pitch to defend
and it's pushed to leg to end the over
on off stump, defended on the front foot
cut off the back foot into the covers
two runs through midwicket. Very well run
again too short, Ponting has plenty of time to rock back and nudge it to leg
on leg stump, Hayden comes forward, massively, and times it down the ground
miles wide of the leg stump, Hayden flicks this down to fine leg
gone! Well bowled, Panesar; he saw Hayden lunging down the pitch, sent it wider of the batsman who drove and got a thick outside edge to Nixon behind the stumps. Super piece of bowling, that
defended firmly on the front foot
lovely flight from Monty; a teasing line on off stump which is defended on the front foot
defended solidly on the front foot
tossed on his leg stump and turned through midwicket
defended on the front foot
defended on the front foot
good line, just outside off and turning back into the batsman who whips it to leg
ooh well bowled - this hurries the right hander who is quickly back into his crease and defending
nicely bowled again from Dalrymple; just outside the off stump, and it's defended off the back foot
pushed off the back foot into the covers
jaffa! Ponting comes forward but it's the arm ball from Dalrymple and he's comprehensively beaten
short and wide of the right-hander's off stump, cut off the back foot
right up in the blockhole and Ponting eases this, with perfect timing, over Monty's head, over long-off and it falls just short of the rope
turned off his legs
on leg stump and Clarke turns it off his legs
on middle-and-leg, Clarke tries to whip it to leg but can't time it
pushed out into the covers
outside off, Ponting comes forward and angles this to cover
turned to leg
firmly defended on the front foot
filthy delivery which didn't get what it deserved: a right, royal spanking. Instead it was pulled, without power, through midwicket
Ponting comes forward and pushes it to mid on
clunked to the bowler's right who dives, athletically and fields
wide down the leg side
slightly short outside the offstump, punched past cover point
outside off stump, punched past point
